<h1>Problem 1140 - 2021 ICMC Round 2, P2 of 4, N</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 9</h2>
<p>Let \(p > 3\) be a prime number. A sequence of \(p-1\) integers \(a_1,a_2, \dots, a_{p-1}\) is called <i>wonky</i> if they are distinct modulo \(p\) and \(a_ia_{i+2} \not\equiv a_{i+1}^2 \pmod p\) for all \(i \in \{1, 2, \dots, p-1\}\), where \(a_p = a_1\) and \(a_{p+1} = a_2\). Does there always exist a wonky sequence such that \[a_1a_2, \qquad a_1a_2+a_2a_3, \qquad \dots, \qquad a_1a_2+\cdots +a_{p-1}a_1,\]are all distinct modulo \(p\)?</p>
